# Japanese Reading Assist Layer Rules

The product serves BJT learners at many Japanese levels. The app must help users read Japanese text without turning the UI into a noisy beginner-only interface.

## Required architecture

- Implement a reusable Japanese text rendering layer, not one-off tooltips per page.
- Use a provider abstraction: `ReadingAssistProvider`, `JapaneseTextAnalyzer`, `DictionaryLookupService`, and user preference policy.
- Persist user reading assist preferences.
- Cache analyzed text by normalized text hash to avoid repeated tokenization.
- Connect selected words/sentences to flashcard creation.
- Support desktop hover/click and mobile tap/bottom-sheet behavior.
- Support accessibility: keyboard focus, screen reader labels, visible focus state.

## Required UX behavior

- Default mode should be clean: hover/tap only, not full furigana everywhere.
- Allow user preference modes: off, hover/tap only, difficult words only, full furigana, beginner mode.
- Do not reveal vocabulary meanings during active timed BJT exam mode unless the mode is practice/help or after the answer is submitted.
- Avoid noisy underlines on every word. Use subtle visual cues.

## Forbidden shortcuts

- Do not implement reading assist as a hard-coded demo tooltip.
- Do not use frontend-only fake dictionary data as source of truth.
- Do not wrap every single kanji character as a word without tokenization.
- Do not analyze the same text on every React render.
- Do not log full private user text into analytics.
- Do not make basic reading support a paid-only feature.

## Production baseline

A valid implementation must include:

- backend analyzer endpoint with typed DTOs
- persistence for preferences and cache
- reusable frontend components
- add-to-flashcard flow
- analytics events
- at least basic admin report view for dictionary gaps / failed tokenization
- tests for analyzer and preference behavior
